      Bobby Jain launch
   =20
 =20
A stylized model of hedge fund management is that in the olden days, hedge =
funds started out as basically one clever investor pursuing one strategy. I=
f it worked out, and if the manager had big aspirations, she might then hir=
e someone else to run a different strategy within the same firm. If it work=
ed out repeatedly over time, eventually the manager would supervise 100 oth=
er managers running 100 strategies, and her job would be not =E2=80=9Ccleve=
r investor=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9Cbuilder of institutions, developer =
of talent and allocator of capital among strategies.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And then=
 the life cycle would repeat: One of the 100 managers working at the big mu=
lti-manager multi-strategy =E2=80=9Cplatform=E2=80=9D would be so successfu=
l running his strategy that he=E2=80=99d leave to start his own hedge fund,=
 one investor pursuing one strategy. And if it worked, etc.But this platfor=
m=C2=A0model has been so successful =E2=80=94=C2=A0as a way to offer uncorr=
elated alpha to clients, and also as a way to extract large fees from them =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and has such economies of scale that it arguably doesn=E2=80=
=99t make sense for the life cycle to repeat anymore. That is, it=E2=80=99s=
 not obvious that being a clever investor is the best preparation for start=
ing a new hedge fund, or that a new single-manager hedge fund is the best w=
ay to start. Maybe what you want is:=09Be a builder of institutions and all=
ocator of capital at a big platform firm.=09Leave to start your own platfor=
m firm, all at once, starting out with scale and lots of different managers=
.It does seem harder to start this way =E2=80=94=C2=A0you have to hire a lo=
t of people before getting investors, and get investors before hiring a lot=
 of people, and build infrastructure before making any money =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but maybe it=E2=80=99s a requirement.=C2=A0Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Hema Parm=
ar reports on Bobby Jain=E2=80=99s hedge fund launch:His vision ... was amb=
itious, even unprecedented. He would hatch a giant, fully formed hedge fund=
 that would trade a half-dozen strategies and employ hundreds of people glo=
bally from day one. It required quickly finding gifted traders amid an expe=
nsive talent war, building complex infrastructure over months and raising e=
nough investor money to pay for it.Failing to achieve even one of those lof=
ty targets could tank the whole thing before it ever got started. Even Jain=
 has likened the maneuver to landing three airplanes at once.Many investors=
 sat on the sidelines, skeptical of the deviation from the typical hedge fu=
nd playbook of starting small and building from there. While Jain initially=
 set out to hit a record of as much as $10 billion, he later halved that go=
al.But Jain, a onetime acolyte of Millennium Management founder Izzy Englan=
der, won votes of confidence from key investors including the Middle Easter=
n sovereign wealth fund, which ultimately handed him about $1 billion. He r=
aised $5.3 billion in total, the biggest launch since ExodusPoint Capital M=
anagement=E2=80=99s record $8 billion debut in 2018. =E2=80=A6Clients who d=
id back the firm say their investment is ultimately a bet on Jain, who help=
ed Millennium push into new strategies and develop its central risk book. N=
ow, he must prove he can deliver Millennium-like results without the resour=
ces of one of the world=E2=80=99s largest hedge funds. =E2=80=A6Jain Global=
 is offering a hedge-fund smorgasbord with more than 40 portfolio managers:=
 It will delve into macroeconomic themes and arbitrage strategies and trade=
 not only stocks and credit instruments, but also physical commodities. It =
will also explore private credit, such as synthetic risk transfers that tak=
e exposure off banks=E2=80=99 balance sheets.=C2=A0The thesis is that the o=
ld model =E2=80=94=C2=A0start=C2=A0with one clever investor doing one thing=
 and then build from there =E2=80=94=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t work anymore:Jain=
 =E2=80=94 who, along with other employees, is kicking in $200 million =E2=
=80=94 has told his investors that starting off big is the most efficient r=
oute to building a multistrat.If a hedge fund bolts on strategies over time=
, it can duplicate systems, manpower and expenses, his thinking goes. Jain =
has concluded that his firm can avoid those inefficiencies by setting up a =
central operating system that=E2=80=99s already prepared for all of its str=
ategies. He=E2=80=99s hoping his fully built-out firm will be able to add a=
ssets and talent in the future without incurring substantial operating cost=
s, those familiar with Jain=E2=80=99s thinking said.=E2=80=9CWe are buildin=
g a single, cross-asset, modern operating platform =E2=80=94 a rare feat in=
 the industry,=E2=80=9D Jain wrote in an investor document seen by Bloomber=
g. =E2=80=9CWhile this is more intensive at launch, it avoids the inherent =
challenges, complexity and cost apparent in a sequential build.=E2=80=9DAls=
o I suppose that what you are pitching to potential clients is not so much =
=E2=80=9CI am a clever investor=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9CI am a success=
ful builder of hedge fund institutions=E2=80=9D; the pitch is not so much a=
bout the investing process as it is about the infrastructure plans.=C2=A0
