      HBS Ponzi
   =20
 =20
Man, the Greenlight Capital alumni events must be a lot of fun. You=E2=80=
=99ve got the Head of Macro guy picketing outside or whatever, and then the=
re=E2=80=99s this guy:The idea sounded solid on the surface. Vlad Artamonov=
 told prospective investors, many of them his former classmates from Harvar=
d Business School, that he=E2=80=99d discovered a hidden way to learn which=
 stocks Warren Buffett was buying early, an edge that would make him a lot =
of money. It involved, he said, combing through esoteric state financial di=
sclosures and then trading on the information =E2=80=94 essentially, a way =
to obtain insider tips legally. =E2=80=9CHave an insane idea,=E2=80=9D he t=
old one investor in the fall of 2022. But it seemed plausible coming from A=
rtamonov, who, in addition to his Ivy League credentials, had spent more th=
an five years at Greenlight Capital, the highly regarded activist hedge fun=
d run by David Einhorn, a self-described admirer of Buffett. He told invest=
ors he aimed for returns of as much as 1,000 percent and wanted to make =E2=
=80=9Chundreds of millions of dollars=E2=80=9D on the play. =E2=80=9CIt is =
really a ridiculous information arbitrage,=E2=80=9D he told another investo=
r that fall. =E2=80=9CBasically getting tomorrow=E2=80=99s newspaper today.=
 Literally having a private time machine.=E2=80=9DWe=E2=80=99ve talked abou=
t Artamonov before. He did not have a time machine; he had a Harvard MBA an=
d a Ponzi scheme. The trick is that he pitched the Ponzi scheme to other Ha=
rvard MBAs, who thought =E2=80=9Cwell that guy can=E2=80=99t be running a P=
onzi scheme, he=E2=80=99s got a Harvard MBA.=E2=80=9D In some ways, a=C2=A0=
genius move, though arguably most=C2=A0Harvard MBAs find career paths that =
are both more lucrative and more legal.That paragraph I quoted is from Jen =
Wieczner=E2=80=99s New York Magazine story about Artamonov, which adds the =
crucial information that he didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0just=C2=A0have a Harvard MB=
A; he also worked at Greenlight, so it was extra-weird that he=E2=80=99d ge=
t into the Ponzi business:As the months passed, the friend reached out to s=
omeone he knew who had also invested with Artamonov and voiced what seemed =
like a crazy, irrational fear. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s no way Vlad would b=
e running a Ponzi scheme, right?=E2=80=9D he asked. The two dismissed it fr=
om their minds. =E2=80=9CWhy would he risk his reputation? It=E2=80=99s a s=
mall amount of money, it=E2=80=99s not rational =E2=80=94 why would he put =
his career on the line?=E2=80=9D they reasoned. =E2=80=9CI think you give a=
 friend the benefit of the doubt.=E2=80=9DI am not sure that there=E2=80=99=
s a satisfying answer to that question, but the article does hint that Arta=
monov was successful early =E2=80=94=C2=A0HBS, Greenlight, expensive Hampto=
ns summers =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it didn=E2=80=99t last: He left Greenlight to=
 start his own fund, it =E2=80=9Cwas not a huge success,=E2=80=9D and he wa=
s downwardly mobile and nostalgic for his time at Greenlight. If you have e=
xpensive tastes, no money, and a nostalgia for the time when you were young=
 and promising and just starting out in a fancy profession, I suppose that =
is how you end up starting a Harvard Business School Ponzi scheme.
