      Cryonics law
   =20
 =20
See, if you go to=C2=A0a=C2=A0regular=C2=A0trusts and estates lawyer, she w=
ill ask you questions like =E2=80=9Cif your spouse and children die before =
you, whom do you want to inherit your estate,=E2=80=9D but if you go to a=
=C2=A0science fiction=C2=A0trusts and estates lawyer, she will ask you ques=
tions like =E2=80=9Cif your frozen head cannot be attached to a fresh body =
and reanimated in 200 years, but your consciousness=C2=A0can be cloned in a=
 computer simulation, would you like your estate to go to the cloned consci=
ousness or stay with the frozen head?=E2=80=9D Meanwhile I suppose if you g=
o to a regular financial planner, he will ask you questions like =E2=80=9Ch=
ow much equity risk are you comfortable taking between now and retirement,=
=E2=80=9D while if you go to a science fiction financial planner, he will a=
sk you questions like =E2=80=9Cwhere are you most comfortable investing for=
 the next 200 years, given that you will not be able to change your asset a=
llocation decisions during that time, because you=E2=80=99ll be dead?=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0When you are a kid, science fiction is fun because it imagines ama=
zing futuristic technologies. And then you grow up and you realize that wha=
t=E2=80=99s=C2=A0really=C2=A0fun are the legal and financial technologies t=
hat are called into being=C2=A0by those physical technologies: Sure sure su=
re reviving a frozen head is great, but how does the frozen head get a cred=
it card? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Erin Schilling reports:Estate attorneys are cr=
eating trusts aimed at extending wealth until people who get cryonically pr=
eserved can be revived, even if it=E2=80=99s hundreds of years later. These=
 revival trusts are an emerging area of law built on a tower of assumptions=
. Still, they=E2=80=99re being taken seriously enough to attract true belie=
vers and merit discussion at industry conferences.=E2=80=9CThe idea of cryo=
preservation has gone from crackpot to merely eccentric,=E2=80=9D said Mark=
 House, an estate lawyer who works with Scottsdale, Ariz.-based Alcor Life =
Extension Foundation, the world=E2=80=99s largest cryonics facility with 1,=
400 members and about 230 people already frozen. =E2=80=9CNow that it=E2=80=
=99s eccentric, it=E2=80=99s kind of in vogue to be interested in it.=E2=80=
=9DHe and others are trying to answer questions that at times seem more lik=
e prompts in a philosophy class.Can money live indefinitely?Are you dead if=
 your body is cryonically preserved?Are you considered revived if you have =
only your brain?And if you=E2=80=99re revived, are you the same person?So=
=C2=A0many good legal questions =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CHouse considers the=
 revived person to be different in the eyes of the law, in part because a p=
erson can=E2=80=99t be the beneficiary of their own trusts=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but also great financial ones.Here=E2=80=99s one: Should you buy B=
itcoin for your long sleep?=C2=A0The argument for Bitcoin is that you can=
=C2=A0hold=C2=A0it, indefinitely, without relying on anyone else: If you pu=
t 10 Bitcoin in a wallet and only you know the private key, and then you di=
e and get frozen and=C2=A0come back in 200 years, no one will have taken yo=
ur Bitcoin, legal rules about inheritance and=C2=A0perpetual trusts don=E2=
=80=99t matter, and you don=E2=80=99t need some succession plan for the tru=
stees and financial advisers who will take care of your assets.
  [3]
=C2=A0You just have to make sure you remember your private key as you=E2=80=
=99re dying. Legal rules can change, human institutions can change, but you=
r Bitcoin is immutable.The argument against Bitcoin is, of course, what if =
people stop valuing Bitcoin? Putting your money in Bitcoin is a hedge again=
st change in other=C2=A0human institutions, but it puts a lot of eggs in th=
e basket of=C2=A0one=C2=A0human institution, =E2=80=9Ctreating Bitcoin as m=
oney.=E2=80=9D
  [4]
=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s a bit weird to bet that that=E2=80=99s more permanent th=
an anything else.More generally, what is money anyway? =E2=80=9CIt may be d=
ifficult to know what role money will play in a post-[artificial general in=
telligence]=C2=A0world,=E2=80=9D says OpenAI to its investors, and what if=
=C2=A0OpenAI=C2=A0gets to artificial general intelligence before anyone get=
s around to unfreezing the heads? You might be leaving your future self all=
 the wrong stuff.=C2=A0
