</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way a Ponzi scheme works, for a wh=
ile, is that (1) you take people=E2=80=99s money, (2) you tell them that th=
ey are earning a nice return on their money and (3) if they want to=C2=A0<e=
m>withdraw=C2=A0</em>their money, with those nice returns, you just <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36001625.196409/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMTMvY2Vsc2l1cy13=
YXMtbHlpbmc_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDcwOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNzA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa4794528" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">give them someone else=E2=80=
=99s money</a>. With enough investors, you can keep this going for a while:=
 There=E2=80=99s plenty of money from new investors to pay off anyone who w=
ants to withdraw, and because everyone who wants to withdraw gets their mon=
ey back,=C2=A0<em>no one suspects anything</em>, so not too many people wit=
hdraw and the system works. Eventually it doesn=E2=80=99t.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">One result of this is that some victims of Ponzi schemes do=
 quite well for themselves: They invest in the Ponzi, they earn a nice retu=
rn, and they withdraw their money before it all collapses. Most of the time=
, these people are not, like, in on the Ponzi; they just had lucky timing.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem comes later. The Ponzi collapse=
s, and some administrator or bankruptcy court is in charge of dividing up t=
he money and paying everyone fairly. Lots of people kept their money in the=
 Ponzi until the end, and will get back only pennies on the dollar. Meanwhi=
le some people withdrew their money a week before the collapse and got back=
 100 cents on the dollar, or more, what with the nice Ponzi returns. Seems =
unfair.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact=C2=A0US bankruptcy law =
has mechanisms for dealing with this: <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/36001625.196409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3V=
zY29kZS90ZXh0LzExLzU0Nw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBafa614b2" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Section =
547(b) of the bankruptcy code</a> allows a bankruptcy estate to claw back s=
ome payments to creditors made within 90 days before bankruptcy, if the com=
pany was insolvent and those payments gave the creditors more than they wou=
ld get in the bankruptcy. So if you withdrew 110 cents on the dollar a day =
before bankruptcy, and everyone else got back 70 cents after bankruptcy, yo=
u have to cough up 40 cents to share with everyone else. And this is true o=
f Ponzi schemes too. Lots of Bernie Madoff=E2=80=99s investors did great, a=
nd <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36001625.196409=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZm9yYmVzLmNvbS9zaXRlcy9jaGFzZXdpdGhvcm4vMjAyMS8wNC8xNC90aG=
UtaW52ZXN0b3JzLXdoby1oYWQtdG8tcGF5LWJhY2stYmlsbGlvbnMtaW4taWxsLWdvdHRlbi1nY=
Wlucy1mcm9tLWJlcm5pZS1tYWRvZmZzLXBvbnppLXNjaGVtZS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bcb29f8ea" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">then had to pay back their winnings</a> to the other, le=
ss fortunate investors.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36001625.196409/aHR0cHM6Ly90aGVkZ=
WZpYW50LmlvL25ld3MvY2VmaS9jZWxzaXVzLWFpbXMtdG8tcmVjb3Zlci11c2QxMDAtbWlsbGlv=
bi1mcm9tLXVzZXJzLXdoby13aXRoZHJldy1mdW5kcy1iZWZvcmUtYmFua3J1cHRjeQ/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB2097ce21" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">so in crypto</a>:</p><blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The administration overseeing now-defunct Celsius=E2=
=80=99s bankruptcy filed legal action on July 1 against users who withdrew =
their funds in the 90 days prior to the firm=E2=80=99s demise.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to Business Wire, the Celsius Litigation Adm=
inistrator filed complaints in the Southern District of New York against ho=
lders with more than $100,000 of withdrawal preference exposure (WPE). Thes=
e are investors who managed to withdraw funds in the 90 days prior to when =
the firm began its bankruptcy proceedings=E2=80=93which took place between =
April 14, 2022 and July 13, 2022.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over 1,50=
0 account holders now face the potential of returning up to $100 million.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAccount holders who withdrew funds =
in the days leading up to Celsius=E2=80=99 bankruptcy have unfairly benefit=
ted at the expense of other account holders since fulfillment of their with=
drawal requests resulted in Celsius being unable to equitably fulfill other=
 withdrawals,=E2=80=9D said Mohsin Meghji, The Celsius Litigation Administr=
ator.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36001625.196409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYnVzaW5lc3N3aXJlLmNvbS9uZXdzL2hvbWUvMjAyNDA3MDE3NjM5OTcvZW4vQ2Vsc2l1cy1Ma=
