order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">an X post from a customer</a> complaining about this treatment. That=
 post includes this fascinating detail: =E2=80=9CThey have more than double=
d the amount of money they are suing for because they changed the ask to cu=
rrent pricing of btc/eth vs originally asking for 2022 pricing.=E2=80=9D<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of crypto firms went bankrupt in=
 the crypto winter of 2022, when crypto prices were low. Now crypto prices =
are higher. The standard approach in US crypto bankruptcies has been that c=
rypto claims =E2=80=94=C2=A0what the bankrupt firm=C2=A0<em>owes=C2=A0</em>=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0are converted into dollars at the time of bankruptcy. If you=
 had one Bitcoin on a crypto platform that blew up in November 2022, your c=
laim in bankruptcy is for about $20,000 (the value of a Bitcoin at the time=
), and if you get back 20 or 70 or 110 cents on the dollar, that means $4,0=
00 or $14,000 or $22,000. But now a Bitcoin is worth something like $55,000=
, so even getting back 110 cents on the dollar on your claim ($22,000) isn=
=E2=80=99t very good. Notably, the FTX bankruptcy=C2=A0will<em>=C2=A0</em>p=
ay something like 118 cents on the dollar on all claims, which <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36001625.196409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDUtMDgvZnR4LWZvdW5kLXRoZ=
S1tb25leT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzA5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9z=
b3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB26e51c72" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">sounds good until you remember<=
/a>=C2=A0that crypto prices have tripled since FTX went bankrupt.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it might not be so clear how avoidance claims =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0what the bankrupt firm=C2=A0<em>is owed=C2=A0</em>by custome=
rs who got out early =E2=80=94=C2=A0are valued. Maybe, if you withdrew a Bi=
tcoin from Celsius just before it went bankrupt, you owe it back one Bitcoi=
n? Or $55,000?<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0This could create a particularly weird result in which the custom=
ers who left their Bitcoins at failing crypto platforms get back $20,000 pe=
r Bitcoin, and customers who took them out have to pay back $55,000 per Bit=
coin. You can=E2=80=99t win either way!</p><table class=3D"liveintent-spons=
