om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Cryonics law</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See, if you go to=C2=A0a=C2=A0<em>regu=
lar=C2=A0</em>trusts and estates lawyer, she will ask you questions like =
=E2=80=9Cif your spouse and children die before you, whom do you want to in=
herit your estate,=E2=80=9D but if you go to a=C2=A0<em>science fiction=C2=
=A0</em>trusts and estates lawyer, she will ask you questions like =E2=80=
=9Cif your frozen head cannot be attached to a fresh body and reanimated in=
 200 years, but your consciousness=C2=A0can be cloned in a computer simulat=
ion, would you like your estate to go to the cloned consciousness or stay w=
ith the frozen head?=E2=80=9D Meanwhile I suppose if you go to a regular fi=
nancial planner, he will ask you questions like =E2=80=9Chow much equity ri=
sk are you comfortable taking between now and retirement,=E2=80=9D while if=
 you go to a science fiction financial planner, he will ask you questions l=
ike =E2=80=9Cwhere are you most comfortable investing for the next 200 year=
s, given that you will not be able to change your asset allocation decision=
s during that time, because you=E2=80=99ll be dead?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When you are a kid, science fiction is fun because =
it imagines amazing futuristic technologies. And then you grow up and you r=
ealize that what=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>fun are the legal and =
financial technologies that are called into being=C2=A0by those physical te=
chnologies: Sure sure sure reviving a frozen head is great, but how does th=
e frozen head get a credit card? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36001625.196409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDctMDkvcmljaC1wZW9wbGUtZnJlZXplLXRoZW1=
zZWx2ZXMtYW5kLWZvcnR1bmVzLWZvci1mdXR1cmUtcmV2aXZhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzA5MjRfTU=
9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVyb=
T0yNDA3MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8299edd=
f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">Erin Schilling reports</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Estate attorneys are creating trusts aimed at extending wealth un=
til people who get cryonically preserved can be revived, even if it=E2=80=
=99s hundreds of years later. These revival trusts are an emerging area of =
law built on a tower of assumptions. Still, they=E2=80=99re being taken ser=
iously enough to attract true believers and merit discussion at industry co=
nferences.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe idea of cryopreserv=
ation has gone from crackpot to merely eccentric,=E2=80=9D said Mark House,=
 an estate lawyer who works with Scottsdale, Ariz.-based Alcor Life Extensi=
on Foundation, the world=E2=80=99s largest cryonics facility with 1,400 mem=
bers and about 230 people already frozen. =E2=80=9CNow that it=E2=80=99s ec=
centric, it=E2=80=99s kind of in vogue to be interested in it.=E2=80=9D</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He and others are trying to answer questions t=
hat at times seem more like prompts in a philosophy class.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Can money live indefinitely?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Are you dead if your body is cryonically preserved?</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Are you considered revived if you have only your brain?</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And if you=E2=80=99re revived, are you the same per=
son?</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So=C2=A0many good legal q=
uestions =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CHouse considers the revived person to be d=
ifferent in the eyes of the law, in part because a person can=E2=80=99t be =
the beneficiary of their own trusts=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but also great =
financial ones.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s one: Should =
you buy Bitcoin for your long sleep?=C2=A0The argument for Bitcoin is that =
you can=C2=A0<em>hold=C2=A0</em>it, indefinitely, without relying on anyone=
 else: If you put 10 Bitcoin in a wallet and only you know the private key,=
 and then you die and get frozen and=C2=A0come back in 200 years, no one wi=
ll have taken your Bitcoin, legal rules about inheritance and=C2=A0perpetua=
l trusts don=E2=80=99t matter, and you don=E2=80=99t need some succession p=
lan for the trustees and financial advisers who will take care of your asse=
ts.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You just have to make sure you remember your private key as you=
=E2=80=99re dying. Legal rules can change, human institutions can change, b=
ut your Bitcoin is immutable.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The argument =
against Bitcoin is, of course, what if people stop valuing Bitcoin? Putting=
 your money in Bitcoin is a hedge against change in <em>other=C2=A0</em>hum=
an institutions, but it puts a lot of eggs in the basket of=C2=A0<em>one=C2=
=A0</em>human institution, =E2=80=9Ctreating Bitcoin as money.=E2=80=9D<a c=
lass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpare=
nt !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s a bit weird to bet that that=E2=80=99s more permanen=
t than anything else.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More generally, what =
is money anyway? =E2=80=9CIt may be difficult to know what role money will =
play in a post-[artificial general intelligence]=C2=A0world,=E2=80=9D <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36001625.196409/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMjAvd2hvLWNvbn=
Ryb2xzLW9wZW5haT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzA5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJ=
nV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5=
c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd1b37afa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">says OpenAI to its inves=
tors</a>, and what if=C2=A0OpenAI=C2=A0gets to artificial general intellige=
nce before anyone gets around to unfreezing the heads? You might be leaving=
 your future self all the wrong stuff.=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"header" wid=
